article.description: Nykesha Sales scored 18 points and was a key part of the interior defense that helped the Orlando Miracle rally to a 66-62 victory over the Cleveland Rockers on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Miracle rally from 14 down to beat Rockers
article.linkText: Sales pitches in 18 points, leads Miracle rally past Rockers
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Nykesha Sales scored 18 points and was a key part of the interior defense that helped the Orlando Miracle rally to a 66-62 victory over the Cleveland Rockers on Wednesday night.

"Cleveland is known for tough defense, so we knew we had to get after it at the defensive end,'' first-year Miracle coach Dee Brown said. "Nykesha did a great job on both ends of the court.''

Shannon Johnson added 13 points for Orlando, which battled back from a 14-point deficit. The Miracle (5-3) took their first lead at 48-47 on an 18-foot jumper by Brooke Wyckoff with 12:08 to play.

"Once again we let it get away,'' Rockers guard Merlakia Jones
said. "We have to find a way to put together two halves. No
excuses. We should have finished this game.''

The teams exchanged the lead until Cleveland went up 57-51 as
Chasity Melvin scored on a layup, Jones followed with two free
throws and Melvin added two more foul shots.

Johnson then scored six consecutive points -- three from the foul
line -- to tie it with 4:16 left. Johnson was 9-for-10 from the free
throw line overall.

"That's a big part of her game, getting to the line,'' Rockers
coach Dan Hughes said. "She's very difficult to defend.''

Johnson made two more free throws with 1:50 to play to put
Orlando ahead to stay at 61-60. Adrienne Johnson followed with a
3-pointer for a 64-60 lead.

Cleveland closed within 64-62 on two free throws by Penny Taylor
with 37 seconds left and, after Orlando missed a shot, got the ball
back with 8.4 seconds to play.

Taylor, in and out of the lineup all night with back spasms,
missed a 3-point attempt with 2 seconds left. Sales grabbed the
rebound, was fouled, and made two free throws.

"Penny had not practiced since Saturday and was a game-time
decision to give it a try,'' Hughes said. "She tried to make a
play there and if it went in, we look pretty.''

The Miracle improved to 3-1 on the road after going 15-33 away from home over their first three seasons.

The Rockers (2-5) dropped to 1-3 at home and lost for the second
time at Gund Arena after leading by at least 14 points. Cleveland
was 14-2 at home last season and won the Eastern Conference with a
22-10 mark.

"We need to establish our defense and sustain our offense,''
Hughes said. "We are a very inconsistent team right now.

"We got the ball inside and shot well in the first half, then we didn't rebound well and were impatient for much of the second half.''

Jones led Cleveland with 14 points, while Melvin scored 10.

   The Rockers, who led 34-20 with 4:28 to play in the first half,
shot 6-for-25 from the field in the second half.

"I told our team that if we cut down the Rockers' shooting percentage we could stay in the game,'' Brown said. "We just kept working and working, hoping they would start missing shots and they did.''

In the teams' first meeting this season, Orlando won 103-99 at home in triple overtime with Johnson scoring a career-high 35 points.
